      <h2>Project Overview</h2>
      <p>As the principal cartographer for the GRID3 project at CIESIN, I developed and managed an enterprise-level map production pipeline for national-scale malaria intervention planning across multiple African countries.</p>
      
      <h2>Key Achievements</h2>
      <p>Developed dozens of complex print-format map templates for routine immunization microplanning and health fieldwork operations. The system was designed to handle simultaneous transmission of thousands of detailed atlas pages over unpredictable internet connections in rural areas.</p>
      
      <p>Established visual specifications for project-wide digital and print cartography, ensuring consistency across all GRID3 data visualizations and public-facing communications materials.</p>
      
      <h2>International Impact</h2>
      <p>Designed and instructed a three-day cartography workshop in Maputo, Mozambique, to transfer map production methodology to the Mozambican national mapping agency, Agência Nacional de Desenvolvimento Geo-Espacial.</p>
      
      <p>Work was featured in the New York Times article "'X' Marks the Spot: Officials Map a Route Out of the Pandemic" and selected for publication in the Esri Map Book Volume 37.</p>
      
      <h2>Technical Implementation</h2>
      <p>Built using ESRI ArcGIS Pro, ArcGIS Online SDK, and Python (ArcPy) for automation. The system integrates with NASA Socioeconomic Data and Applications Center and maintains the GRID3 data hub portal.</p>
      
      <h2>Publications</h2>
      <p>Co-authored "Developing High-Resolution Population and Settlement Data for Impactful Malaria Interventions in Zambia" (2022) published in the Journal of Environmental and Public Health. Presented findings at the 30th International Cartographic Conference in Florence, Italy.</p>
